<font color="#FF0000">THE UNNECESSARY WAR</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 30 22:52:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I presume everyone has read Jeffery's posts and if not I urge you to do so.  Even if you have, you might want to re-read them.  They make a lot more sense than some of the name-calling that has been going on here.  The bottom line is that hundreds of thousands of people were killed and millions suffered greviously for nothing. The American people lost faith in their government and the morale of our armed forces was shattered: for nothing.  Why did this tragedy happen?  The blame can be laid at the feet of our &quot;leaders&quot; on a bipartisan basis:  Kennedy, Johnson, Rusk, McNamara, Nixon, Kissinger, and so on.  Despite the intelligence resources available to them, they seemed woefully ignorant of the peoples, cultures, and history of southeast Asia.  The military leadership was just as unimaginative.  Anyone interested in learning how unnecessary the Vietnam War was, how easily it could have been avoided, and how much sooner it could have been ended should read Ten Thousand Day War: Vietnam 1945-1975, by Michael Maclear.  In the beginning, in 1945, the U.S. actively supported Ho Chi Minh.  Then, when the French wanted to return, we supported them.  That was our first mistake of many.<br><br>
You know, I attended a fairly conservative college in the 60's: very few &quot;student radicals&quot; or &quot;doves.&quot;  There were in fact many &quot;hawks&quot; who passionately argued that our national honor required that we fulfill our &quot;commitment&quot; to the South Vietmanese, or if we didn't stop the &quot;communists&quot; there, we would have to do on the California beaches.  But did these guys put on a uniform?  No!  They took full advantage of their student deferments just as the anti-war people did.  My room mate was a prime example.  If that wasn't bad enough, there were actually a number of young Vietmanese men attending school there on student visas!  Yes, they were going to college in the states, while Americans were in Vietnam fighting and dying, allegedly to protect these same Vietmanese from the communists. 
